			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Ok, Joey.  You asked&#8230;<BR>
<BR>
We have recently discovered a bug that appears to modify the stats of charms.  This is a client side error and is strictly visual.  Any modified stats will not be interpreted by the servers as legitimate values.<BR>
<BR>
The error will be corrected as soon as possible.<BR>
<BR>
-The Sony Programming Team<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There is a way (which I'm not going to explain...) to make it look like your charms are gaining a lot of extra stats.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
OK, tell everyone they can change their visual stats.  I had no clue that this could be done until reading about it here.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;If you see this happening, please do not think that your charm actually has those stats and run of thinking that you are now invincible. You're not.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Be more professional.  This is terminology used by a parent on their kid.  Treat a kid, like a kid, and he will behave like a kid.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We'll fix this bug when we can.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Everything has a priority because you don't know how it has impacted every single customer.  I have learned that there are always people who are impacted by bugs in different ways. This is an unacceptable statement, which should never be sent to a customer.  It sounds like you are too busy to help and that is NEVER the case.<BR>
   <BR>
In conclusion, my post was not based on this statement but MANY by Alan and others that are poorly worded.  It contributes to the atmosphere of immaturity and hostility.  It is because of communications on the lower level rather than the higher.<BR>
<BR>
Hey Joey, get sedated.<BR>

				</font>
